lok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Guy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of a compound name starting with <i>witu</i> ‘wood’ or <i>wīt</i> ‘wide’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. In Old French initial <i>w-</i> regularly became <i>gu-</i>. The usual Norman forms of the name were <i>Gy</i> or <i>Guido</i>. In medieval Latin the same name is found as <i>Wido</i>. It was a popular name among the Normans, enhanced no doubt by the romance of Guy of Warwick, recounting the exploits of a folk hero of the Crusades."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guy I DE CHATILLON was born about 1020, in Châtillon-sur-Marne, Reims, Marne, Champagne-Ardenne, France, his father, Milo   van Châtillon , was 38 and his mother,  Avernelle de Montfort, was 34. He married Emmergarde VAN CHOISY. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. He died after 1089."},"et":{"environ 1020–après 1089":"umbes 1020–pärast 1089","1020–1089":"1020–1089","–1099":"–1099","1014–1101":"1014–1101","1038–Male":"1038–Surnud","1043–1097":"1043–1097","1045–1103":"1045–1103","1047–Male":"1047–Surnud","1050–1089":"1050–1089","0983–1044":"0983–1044","0988–1031":"0988–1031","AFT 1045":"pärast 1045","environ 1020":"umbes 1020","1044":"1044","1099":"1099","1043":"1043","1031":"1031","1097":"1097","1020":"1020","1050":"1050","0983":"0983","1038":"10